BT 1 0 0 1 0 75 Tm 12 TL /F1 9 Tf 0 0 0 rg (From the AnchorForge 100K suite, the collapse probability P_collapse\(gamma\) transitions from 0.1% to 94.6% over a) Tj T* (gamma range of 0.0619 to 0.0944 -- a factor of 1.53x. This is sharp but not infinitely sharp. The Lee-Yang theorem \(Lee &) Tj T* (Yang 1952\) explains exactly why: in a finite system, the partition function has no zeros on the real axis \(no true phase) Tj T* (transition\). Instead, the zeros lie in the complex gamma-plane, approaching the real axis as system size N -) Tj (> inf. The) Tj T* (finite-size rounding of the transition -- the observed width DELTAgamma/gamma_c ~= 0.2 -- is directly related to the) Tj T* (imaginary part of the nearest Lee-Yang zero. This paper derives the Lee-Yang zero position from the AnchorForge data,) Tj T* (identifies the finite-size scaling behavior, and predicts how the transition sharpens as N increases.) Tj T* ET
